tutor_usage() {
  local topic="${1:-overview}"

  case "$topic" in
    overview | help | -h | --help)
      cat <<EOF
Nomad manager tutor

Usage:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} tutor [topic]

Mental model:
  nomad-manager works at the node and integration layer.
  It installs Nomad, writes managed config files, restarts nomad.service,
  and validates local config before keeping changes.
  Use nomad-job when you are ready to create, validate and run job files.

Workflows:
  vault-secret-job  Install Vault and Nomad, then run a job that reads a secret.
  web-service       Prepare Docker and run an HTTP service job.
  private-image     Configure registry auth and run a private image.
  service-update    Review a plan and roll out a new job version.

References:
  install           Install and verify a single-node Nomad server/client.
  docker            Configure Docker driver behavior and image pull auth.
  vault             Point Nomad at Vault without creating Vault-side objects.
  vault-jwt         Link Nomad workload identity to Vault JWT Auth.
  consul            Point Nomad at Consul and verify reachability.
  ui                Manage Nomad Web UI config.
  job               Use nomad-job to generate, validate and run jobs.
  uninstall         Choose a conservative or destructive removal level.

Troubleshooting:
  troubleshoot-job  Inspect job allocations, logs and scheduler decisions.
  troubleshoot      Check Nomad service, config, cluster and integrations.

Command help:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker --help
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt --help
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} host-volume --help

Example:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} tutor install
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} tutor vault-secret-job
EOF
      ;;
    install)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: install Nomad single node
Use when: You need a local Nomad server/client managed by this tool.
Outcome: A running single-node Nomad service with management metadata.

Before you start:
  Run on Linux with root privilege or sudo.
  Confirm outbound access to HashiCorp releases, or configure http_proxy/https_proxy.
  Choose whether ACL bootstrap should run during install.

1. Install latest Nomad:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} install

2. Install through an HTTP proxy:
   http_proxy=http://10.2.1.107:7190 https_proxy=http://10.2.1.107:7190 ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} install

3. Load the bootstrap ACL token after install:
   source ~/nomad.acl

4. Check service and cluster state:
   systemctl status nomad
   nomad server members
   nomad node status

5. Check installed management snapshot and audit log:
   ${TOOL_ENTRY} help
   cat ${INSTALL_METADATA_FILE}
   tail -n 20 ${AUDIT_LOG_FILE}

Verify:
  systemctl status nomad shows active.
  nomad server members lists this node.
  nomad node status lists a ready client.

Common failures:
  Release download blocked by network or proxy settings.
  Missing root privilege prevents service and file installation.
  ACL bootstrap token was not loaded before running nomad CLI commands.

Notes:
  install writes default managed telemetry and Docker config files.
  These files are managed by this tool, not generated by Nomad itself.
  Config files are stored in ${CONFIG_DIR}.
  Runtime data is stored in ${DATA_DIR}; the Nomad agent data_dir is ${NOMAD_AGENT_DATA_DIR}.
EOF
      ;;
    docker)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: Docker driver management
Use when: Nomad clients should run Docker tasks or pull private images.
Outcome: Docker driver settings that match your scheduling and security needs.

Before you start:
  Docker must be installed on the Nomad client.
  Decide whether privileged tasks and host volume mounts are allowed.
  Prepare a Docker auth config if private images are required.

1. Check Docker and Nomad driver state:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor
   nomad node status -self

2. Enable Docker plugin config with the current convenience defaults:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker enable --allow-privileged true --volumes true

3. Harden Docker defaults when privileged jobs and host mounts are not needed:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker enable --allow-privileged false --volumes false

4. Temporarily deny scheduling Docker tasks:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker disable-driver

5. Allow Docker scheduling again:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker enable-driver

Verify:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor reports Docker CLI, daemon and socket checks.
  nomad node status -self shows docker in the driver list.

Common failures:
  Docker daemon is not running.
  /var/run/docker.sock is not reachable by the Nomad agent.
  docker is still denied by the client driver denylist.

Notes:
  docker disable removes only the managed Docker plugin config.
  docker disable-driver changes the Nomad client driver denylist.
  Use --auth-config when tasks must pull from a private registry.
EOF
      ;;
    vault)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: Nomad Vault integration config
Use when: Nomad jobs need workload identity tokens for Vault.
Outcome: Managed Nomad Vault config, ready to pair with Vault auth and policies.

Before you start:
  Vault should be reachable from the Nomad node.
  Decide the Vault address, namespace, audience and token exposure method.
  Use vault-jwt when you also need Vault auth, policy and role setup.

1. Configure Nomad to know where Vault is:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault enable --address http://127.0.0.1:8200 --aud vault.io --ttl 1h

2. Check the generated Nomad config and Vault health:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault doctor --address http://127.0.0.1:8200

3. Use a Vault namespace when needed:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault enable --address https://vault.example.com:8200 --namespace team-a --aud vault.io

4. Remove only the managed Nomad Vault config:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault disable

Verify:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault doctor --address http://127.0.0.1:8200
  nomad config validate ${CONFIG_DIR}

Common failures:
  Vault is sealed or not reachable from the Nomad node.
  TLS CA, cert or namespace options do not match Vault.
  Vault-side auth method, role or policy has not been created yet.

Notes:
  This config only connects Nomad to Vault.
  Vault auth methods, policies and roles still need to exist in Vault.
  Use ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt apply when you want this tool to create the linked Vault objects.
EOF
      ;;
    vault-jwt)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: Nomad workload identity with Vault JWT Auth
Use when: Nomad jobs should authenticate to Vault without static Vault tokens.
Outcome: A saved JWT profile and an example job that can read allowed secrets.

Before you start:
  Nomad and Vault should both be running.
  Vault must be initialized and unsealed.
  VAULT_TOKEN must allow auth method, policy and role changes.
  The --nomad-addr value must be reachable from Vault for JWKS discovery.

1. Plan the full Nomad + Vault JWT configuration:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt plan --profile default --vault-addr http://127.0.0.1:8200 --nomad-addr http://10.2.37.64:4646

2. Apply the configuration with a Vault token in the environment:
   export VAULT_TOKEN=<redacted>
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt apply --profile default --vault-addr http://127.0.0.1:8200 --nomad-addr http://10.2.37.64:4646 --secret-path kv/data/app

3. Check all linked pieces:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt doctor --profile default

4. Generate a job example that uses the profile:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt job-example --profile default --job app --secret kv/data/app --out jobs/app-vault.nomad.hcl

5. Run the generated job:
   nomad-job validate jobs/app-vault.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job apply jobs/app-vault.nomad.hcl --auto-approve

Verify:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt doctor --profile default
  vault read auth/jwt-nomad/role/nomad-workloads
  nomad-job status app

Common failures:
  Vault cannot fetch Nomad JWKS from --nomad-addr.
  VAULT_TOKEN lacks permission to write auth, policy or role objects.
  Secret path passed to the job is not allowed by the generated policy.

Notes:
  apply writes Nomad Vault config, enables or reuses Vault JWT Auth, writes policy and role,
  then saves the profile under ${VAULT_JWT_PROFILE_DIR}.
  For production, pass concrete --secret-path values instead of relying on broad defaults.
EOF
      ;;
    vault-secret-job)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: install Vault and Nomad, then run a job that reads a Vault secret
Use when: You want an end-to-end local proof of Nomad reading a Vault KV secret.
Outcome: A running Nomad allocation that reads kv/data/app through Vault.

Before you start:
  Run this on a test node first.
  Use placeholder secret values when learning the flow.
  Keep the Vault init JSON readable only by trusted administrators.

1. Install, initialize and unseal Vault:
   vault-manager install
   vault-manager init --key-shares 1 --key-threshold 1 --out /opt/vault/init/vault-init.json
   vault-manager unseal --keys-file /opt/vault/init/vault-init.json

2. Export Vault address and a setup token:
   export VAULT_ADDR=http://127.0.0.1:8200
   export VAULT_TOKEN=<root-token-from-/opt/vault/init/vault-init.json>

3. Enable KV v2 once and write an application secret:
   vault secrets enable -path=kv kv-v2
   vault kv put kv/app value='my-secret-value'

4. Install Nomad and load the bootstrap ACL token:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} install
   source ~/nomad.acl

5. Link Nomad workload identity to Vault JWT Auth:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt apply --profile default --vault-addr http://127.0.0.1:8200 --nomad-addr http://127.0.0.1:4646 --secret-path kv/data/app

6. Generate and run a job that reads kv/data/app:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt job-example --profile default --job app --secret kv/data/app --out jobs/app-vault.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job validate jobs/app-vault.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job apply jobs/app-vault.nomad.hcl --auto-approve

7. Inspect the allocation:
   nomad-job status app
   nomad alloc status
   nomad alloc logs <alloc-id> app

Verify:
  vault kv get kv/app returns the secret through the Vault CLI.
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt doctor --profile default succeeds.
  nomad alloc logs <alloc-id> app shows the job could read the template output.

Common failures:
  Vault is sealed after install or restart.
  KV v2 CLI path kv/app is confused with API/template path kv/data/app.
  Vault cannot reach Nomad JWKS when Nomad is bound only to localhost on another node.

Notes:
  vault kv put uses the KV CLI path kv/app.
  Nomad templates and Vault policies use the KV v2 API path kv/data/app.
  If kv/ is already enabled, skip the vault secrets enable command.
  If Vault and Nomad are on different nodes, set --nomad-addr to an address reachable from Vault.
EOF
      ;;
    web-service)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: deploy a Docker web service
Use when: You want a reachable HTTP service from a Docker image.
Outcome: A running Nomad service that you can inspect and test with curl.

Before you start:
  Nomad should be installed and healthy.
  Docker driver should pass ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor.
  Load the ACL token with source ~/nomad.acl if ACLs are enabled.

1. Make sure Nomad can run Docker tasks:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor
   source ~/nomad.acl

2. Scaffold a service with a static host port and HTTP health check:
   nomad-job scaffold docker --job web --image nginx:1.27 --port http:8080:80 --check-http / --cpu 200 --memory 128 --out jobs/web.nomad.hcl

3. Validate, plan and apply:
   nomad-job validate jobs/web.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job plan jobs/web.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job apply jobs/web.nomad.hcl --auto-approve

4. Inspect and test:
   nomad-job status web
   nomad alloc status
   curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/

Verify:
  nomad-job status web shows a running allocation.
  curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/ returns the web service response.

Common failures:
  Docker driver is disabled or Docker daemon is down.
  Static port 8080 is already occupied.
  ACL token was not loaded before planning or applying the job.

Notes:
  Use a static host port only when you need a predictable address.
  For multiple instances, prefer dynamic ports and service discovery.
EOF
      ;;
    private-image)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: run jobs from a private Docker registry
Use when: Nomad tasks must pull images from a private registry.
Outcome: A Nomad client with Docker auth and a job that pulls a private image.

Before you start:
  Push the target image before creating the Nomad job.
  Run docker login on each Nomad client that may pull the image.
  Store the copied Docker config with restrictive permissions.

1. Create a Docker auth config on the Nomad client:
   docker login registry.example.com
   sudo install -d -m 0750 /etc/nomad.d/docker-auth
   sudo install -m 0600 ~/.docker/config.json /etc/nomad.d/docker-auth/config.json

2. Point the Nomad Docker driver at the auth config:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker enable --auth-config /etc/nomad.d/docker-auth/config.json --allow-privileged false --volumes false
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor

3. Scaffold and run a private-image job:
   nomad-job scaffold docker --job api --image registry.example.com/team/api:1.0 --port http:8080:8080 --check-http /health --out jobs/api.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job apply jobs/api.nomad.hcl --auto-approve

Verify:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor succeeds after enabling --auth-config.
  nomad alloc status <alloc-id> does not show image pull errors.

Common failures:
  Docker auth config is unreadable by the Nomad process.
  The registry hostname differs between docker login and the image name.
  The image tag has not been pushed.

Notes:
  Keep the Docker auth config readable only by trusted administrators.
  Image pull failures usually show up in allocation events and client logs.
EOF
      ;;
    service-update)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: validate, plan and update a running service
Use when: You need to roll out a new job definition for an existing service.
Outcome: A new job version deployed after validation and plan review.

Before you start:
  Keep the existing job name.
  Know where to find the previous job version or nomad job history.
  Confirm the new image tag exists before applying.

1. Generate or edit the next job version:
   nomad-job scaffold docker --job web --image registry.example.com/team/web:1.1 --port http:8080:8080 --check-http /health --out jobs/web.nomad.hcl --force

2. Validate and review the plan before changing the running job:
   nomad-job validate jobs/web.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job plan jobs/web.nomad.hcl

3. Apply when the plan is expected:
   nomad-job apply jobs/web.nomad.hcl

4. Watch deployment state:
   nomad-job status web
   nomad job history web
   nomad alloc status

Verify:
  nomad-job status web shows healthy allocations after the update.
  nomad job history web includes the new version.

Common failures:
  The plan shows a replacement that was not expected.
  Health checks fail and the deployment rolls back.
  Static ports block parallel old/new allocations.

Notes:
  Generated jobs include update settings with auto_revert=true.
  Keep old job files or use nomad job history when you need a rollback reference.
EOF
      ;;
    troubleshoot-job)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: troubleshoot Nomad job failures
Use when: A job is pending, failing, restarting or not reachable.
Outcome: A focused checklist for locating the likely failure point.

Before you start:
  Get the job name and an allocation ID if one exists.
  Check Nomad state before changing config.

1. Start with job and allocation state:
   nomad-job status app
   nomad alloc status

2. Inspect allocation events and logs:
   nomad alloc status <alloc-id>
   nomad alloc logs <alloc-id> <task>
   nomad alloc logs -stderr <alloc-id> <task>

3. Check the generated job and scheduler decision:
   nomad job inspect app
   nomad job status app
   nomad eval status <eval-id>

4. Check common node-side causes:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor
   nomad node status -self
   journalctl -u nomad -n 100 --no-pager

Verify:
  Allocation events should narrow the issue to scheduling, image pull, ports, health checks or Vault.
  Task logs should show whether the process starts successfully.

Common failures:
  Image pull auth, occupied static ports, missing host paths, failed health checks,
  insufficient resources, Vault policy mismatch, or Vault auth/JWKS reachability.
EOF
      ;;
    consul)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: Nomad Consul integration config
Use when: Nomad should integrate with a local or remote Consul agent.
Outcome: Managed Consul config with reachability checks.

Before you start:
  Confirm the Consul HTTP address and whether it uses TLS.
  Prepare CA, cert and key files if Consul requires client TLS.

1. Enable Consul integration for a local Consul agent:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul enable --address 127.0.0.1:8500

2. Enable Consul integration with TLS:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul enable --address consul.service.consul:8501 --ssl true --verify true

3. Check Consul config and leader endpoint reachability:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul doctor --address 127.0.0.1:8500

4. Remove only the managed Consul config:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul disable

Verify:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul doctor --address 127.0.0.1:8500
  nomad config validate ${CONFIG_DIR}

Common failures:
  Using HTTP options against a HTTPS Consul listener.
  TLS verification fails because CA or cert files are missing.
  Consul is reachable locally but not from the Nomad node.

Notes:
  enable writes only this tool's managed Consul config file.
  doctor checks local config validation and Consul leader endpoint reachability.
EOF
      ;;
    ui)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: Nomad Web UI management
Use when: You need to enable, disable or customize Nomad UI settings.
Outcome: Managed UI config that matches the desired exposure state.

Before you start:
  Decide whether the UI should be available, disabled, or left to Nomad defaults.
  Prepare Vault or Consul URLs only if you want UI navigation links.

1. Enable UI customization and optional links:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} ui enable --vault-url https://vault.example.com:8200 --consul-url https://consul.example.com:8501

2. Disable the Web UI:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} ui disable

3. Restore Nomad default UI behavior:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} ui reset

Verify:
  nomad config validate ${CONFIG_DIR}
  systemctl status nomad

Common failures:
  ui reset removes managed config and may re-enable the UI because Nomad defaults to enabled.
  Invalid color or URL values produce unexpected UI display.

Notes:
  ui disable writes ui.enabled=false.
  ui reset removes the managed UI config. Nomad defaults ui.enabled to true, so reset can make UI available again.
EOF
      ;;
    job)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: create and run a Nomad job
Use when: You want the companion nomad-job helper for job file operations.
Outcome: A concise generate, validate, apply and stop command sequence.

Before you start:
  Install Nomad first and load ACL credentials if needed.
  Enable Docker before running Docker jobs.

1. Generate a Docker job HCL:
   nomad-job scaffold docker --job web --image nginx:1.27 --port http:8080:80 --out jobs/web.nomad.hcl

2. Validate and plan:
   nomad-job validate jobs/web.nomad.hcl
   nomad-job plan jobs/web.nomad.hcl

3. Apply:
   nomad-job apply jobs/web.nomad.hcl --auto-approve

4. Inspect and stop:
   nomad-job status web
   nomad-job stop web

5. Convert from Docker Compose:
   nomad-job compose convert docker-compose.yml --out jobs/compose.nomad.hcl

Verify:
  nomad-job status web shows the job after apply.
  nomad alloc status shows allocations and task states.

Common failures:
  Running nomad-job before Nomad is installed.
  Applying a job without reviewing the plan.
  Docker jobs fail because the Docker driver is not healthy.
EOF
      ;;
    uninstall)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: uninstall Nomad safely
Use when: You need to remove Nomad runtime, tools or audit metadata.
Outcome: A removal command that matches the intended cleanup scope.

Before you start:
  Decide whether audit logs and installed tool snapshots must be kept.
  Back up any data or config you may need later.

1. Remove Nomad runtime only. Keep installed management tools, metadata and audit logs:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} uninstall

2. Remove runtime and installed management scripts. Keep metadata and audit logs:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} uninstall --remove-tools

3. Remove runtime, tools, metadata and audit logs:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} uninstall --purge

Verify:
  systemctl status nomad should no longer show a running service after uninstall.
  Check ${NOMAD_ROOT_DIR} only after deciding whether data should remain.

Common failures:
  Using --purge when audit logs or metadata were still needed.
  Expecting uninstall to remove all tool snapshots without --remove-tools or --purge.

Notes:
  The default uninstall is intentionally conservative so audit history remains available.
EOF
      ;;
    troubleshoot)
      cat <<EOF
Scenario: Nomad troubleshooting
Use when: Nomad service, config validation or integrations look unhealthy.
Outcome: A general diagnostics checklist for Nomad itself.

Before you start:
  Avoid changing config until you know whether the problem is service, config, cluster or integration state.

1. Check service logs:
   systemctl status nomad
   journalctl -u nomad -n 100 --no-pager

2. Validate local config:
   nomad config validate ${CONFIG_DIR}

3. Check cluster and client state:
   nomad server members
   nomad node status
   nomad node status -self

4. Check common integrations:
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} docker doctor
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault doctor --address http://127.0.0.1:8200
   ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul doctor --address 127.0.0.1:8500

5. Check management metadata and audit history:
   cat ${INSTALL_METADATA_FILE}
   tail -n 50 ${AUDIT_LOG_FILE}

Verify:
  nomad config validate ${CONFIG_DIR} succeeds.
  nomad server members and nomad node status show the expected node.

Common failures:
  A managed config file was changed outside the tool.
  Nomad cannot restart after a config validation or service failure.
  Integration doctor commands point to Vault, Consul or Docker instead of Nomad itself.
EOF
      ;;
    *)
      return 1
      ;;
  esac
}

vault_jwt_usage() {
  cat <<EOF
Nomad + Vault JWT workload identity

Link Nomad workload identity to Vault JWT Auth, save the profile, and generate
job examples that read allowed Vault secrets.

Usage:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt plan --profile <NAME> [options]
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt apply --profile <NAME> [options]
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt status --profile <NAME>
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt doctor --profile <NAME>
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt job-example --profile <NAME> --job <NAME> --secret <PATH> --out <FILE> [--force]

Commands:
  plan          Show the Nomad and Vault changes that would be made.
  apply         Write Nomad config, Vault JWT Auth config, policy and role.
  status        Print the saved profile and linked object names.
  doctor        Check the saved profile, Nomad JWKS reachability and Vault objects.
  job-example   Generate a Nomad job file that uses the saved profile.

Options for plan/apply:
  --profile <NAME>            Required profile name
  --vault-addr <URL>          Vault API address
  --vault-namespace <NAME>    Vault Enterprise namespace for Vault CLI calls
  --nomad-addr <URL>          Nomad HTTP address reachable by Vault for JWKS
  --nomad-jwks-url <URL>      Override JWKS URL, default: <nomad-addr>/.well-known/jwks.json
  --auth-path <PATH>          Vault JWT auth path, default: jwt-nomad
  --role <NAME>               Vault JWT role, default: nomad-workloads
  --policy <NAME>             Vault policy name, default: nomad-workloads
  --aud <VALUE>               JWT audience, default: vault.io
  --ttl <DURATION>            Nomad identity and Vault token TTL, default: 1h
  --secret-path <PATH>        Secret path allowed by generated policy, repeatable
                               default: kv/data/*
  --policy-file <FILE>        Use custom Vault policy HCL instead of generated policy
  --force                     Allow replacing an existing profile with different values

Environment:
  VAULT_TOKEN must be available for apply/status/doctor when Vault requires auth,
  unless the Vault CLI can authenticate through another configured method.

What apply does:
  1. Write Nomad vault config: ${VAULT_CONFIG}
  2. Validate Nomad config and restart nomad.service
  3. Wait until Nomad JWKS URL is reachable
  4. Enable or reuse Vault JWT auth at auth/<auth-path>
  5. Write Vault JWT config, policy and role
  6. Save the profile for status/doctor/job-example

Vault role:
  apply writes claim mappings for nomad_namespace, nomad_job_id and nomad_task,
  then issues renewable service tokens with token_explicit_max_ttl=0.

Policy notes:
  The default generated policy allows kv/data/*.
  For production, pass one or more concrete --secret-path values.
  Use --policy-file when generated policy rules are not strict enough.

Profile file:
  ${VAULT_JWT_PROFILE_DIR}/<PROFILE>.env

Examples:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt plan --profile default --vault-addr http://127.0.0.1:8200 --nomad-addr http://10.2.37.64:4646
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt apply --profile default --vault-addr http://127.0.0.1:8200 --nomad-addr http://10.2.37.64:4646 --secret-path kv/data/app
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt doctor --profile default
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault-jwt job-example --profile default --job app --secret kv/data/app --out jobs/app.nomad.hcl
EOF
}

vault_usage() {
  cat <<EOF
Nomad Vault integration config

Write or remove the Nomad-side Vault integration config. This does not create
Vault auth methods, policies or roles.

Usage:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault enable --address <URL> [options]
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault disable
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault doctor [--address <URL>] [--namespace <NAME>]

Options:
  --address <URL>               Vault API address, for example https://vault.service.consul:8200
  --ca-file <FILE>              Vault CA certificate file
  --ca-path <DIR>               Vault CA certificate directory
  --cert-file <FILE>            Client certificate file
  --key-file <FILE>             Client key file
  --namespace <NAME>            Vault Enterprise namespace
  --jwt-auth-backend-path <PATH>  JWT auth backend path, default: jwt-nomad
  --aud <CSV>                   Workload identity audience list, default: vault.io
  --ttl <DURATION>              Workload identity TTL, default: 1h
  --env <true|false>            Expose identity token in env, default: false
  --file <true|false>           Expose identity token in file, default: true

Behavior:
  enable writes ${VAULT_CONFIG}, validates Nomad config and restarts nomad.service.
  disable removes only the managed Vault config file.
  doctor is read-only. It checks managed config, Nomad config validation, vault CLI
  availability and Vault health endpoint reachability.
  Use vault-jwt apply when Vault-side JWT auth, policy and role should be created too.

Examples:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault enable --address https://vault.service.consul:8200 --aud vault.io --ttl 1h
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault doctor --address https://vault.service.consul:8200
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} vault disable
EOF
}

consul_usage() {
  cat <<EOF
Nomad Consul integration config

Write or remove the Nomad-side Consul integration config and verify Consul
reachability from the Nomad node.

Usage:
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul enable --address <URL> [options]
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul disable
  ${NOMAD_MANAGER_CMD} consul doctor [--address <URL>] [--ssl <true|false>]

Options:
  --address <URL>      Consul HTTP address, for example 127.0.0.1:8500
